{"id":"2212.01781","submitter":"Yanhong Zhu","authors":"Junyang Zhang and Yanhong Zhu","title":"A note on regular sets in Cayley graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A subset $R$ of the vertex set of a graph $\\Gamma$ is said to be\n$(\\kappa,\\tau)$-regular if $R$ induces a $\\kappa$-regular subgraph and every\nvertex outside $R$ is adjacent to exactly $\\tau$ vertices in $R$. In\nparticular, if $R$ is a $(\\kappa,\\tau)$-regular set of some Cayley graph on a\nfinite group $G$, then $R$ is called a $(\\kappa,\\tau)$-regular set of $G$. Let\n$H$ be a non-trivial normal subgroup of $G$, and $\\kappa$ and $\\tau$ a pair of\nintegers satisfying $0\\leq\\kappa\\leq|H|-1$, $1\\leq\\tau\\leq|H|$ and\n$\\gcd(2,|H|-1)\\mid\\kappa$. It is proved that (i) if $\\tau$ is even, then $H$ is\na $(\\kappa,\\tau)$-regular set of $G$; (ii) if $\\tau$ is odd, then $H$ is a\n$(\\kappa,\\tau)$-regular set of $G$ if and only if it is a $(0,1)$-regular set\nof $G$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 4 Dec 2022 10:04:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
